messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full HTTP request path
- /clients/{id}

Why: In index.js, the app uses app.use('/clients', clientRoutes). In routes/clients.js, the routes that take an id are defined as:
- PATCH '/:id' -> updateClient
- DELETE '/:id' -> deleteClient
So the concrete full path for an id-based request is /clients/{id}.

HTTP methods acceptance (based strictly on the code)
- All methods acceptable: No
  - Only PATCH and DELETE are defined for the /clients/{id} path.
- HEAD: No
  - There is no GET route for /clients/{id}, and Express does not automatically provide HEAD unless a corresponding GET route exists. Therefore HEAD is not acceptable for this path as implemented.
- POST: No
  - POST is defined only for '/clients/' (creating a new client), not for '/clients/{id}'.
- OPTIONS: No
  - No explicit OPTIONS handler is defined for this path.
- TRACE: No
  - No TRACE handler is defined.
- GET: No
  - There is no GET '/:id' route for /clients/{id}.
- PUT: No
  - No PUT '/:id' route is defined.
- DELETE: Yes
  - DELETE '/:id' is defined and wired to deleteClient.
- PATCH: Yes
  - PATCH '/:id' is defined and wired to updateClient.

Explanation
- The routes file defines two id-based operations: PATCH /:id and DELETE /:id, which correspond to /clients/{id} when mounted under the /clients prefix in index.js.
- There are no route definitions for GET, PUT, POST, HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE, or any other method for the /clients/{id} path, so those methods are not acceptable for this endpoint according to the code.
- HEAD would only be automatically supported if there were a corresponding GET route for the same path; since there isnâ€™t, HEAD is not considered acceptable here.
